##Introduction to the Postal History of Madagascar

##British

Prior to 1884 a local postmaster was elected from British residents in {[wi:Antananarivo}}. The postmaster would collect the mail
from the residents nad forward them by runner to Tamatave. At {{wi:Tamatave}}, the postal charges were debited to the British Consulate
by the French post office and the mail was dispatched to the U.K. via Mauritius, Reunion, Zanzibar or Natal.

In 1884 Mr. W. C. Pickersgill, the newly appointed British Vice Consul at Antananarivo, 
organized the British Consular Mail.

A March edition of the Madagascar Times carried a notification that postal franks could be purchased at the Vice-Consulate
in payment for postal services at the scale laid down (letter 2d. for each 15 grammes for 
the runner service charge).


